<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Grafting Clips for Tomato Seedlings</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The right clip keeps alignment stable without slowing growth.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, 2.5–3.0 mm silicone grafting clips are the best choice for tomato seedlings because they match typical stem thickness and hold securely without constricting growth.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Tomato grafting is more forgiving than cucumbers, but clip choice still matters. The goal is to maintain clean alignment while the graft heals, without damaging the stem or restricting expansion.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most problems come from mismatched sizing or clips that apply uneven pressure.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Picks: What Actually Works</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> 2.5–3.0 mm silicone clips — ideal for most tomato grafting stages.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for early grafting:</strong> 2.0–2.5 mm clips — better fit for thinner seedlings.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for thicker stems:</strong> 3.5 mm clips — useful for later-stage or vigorous plants.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Matching clip size to stem diameter is the single biggest factor in graft success.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Tomatoes Need Slightly Larger Clips</h2>

  <p>
    Tomato seedlings develop thicker stems than cucumbers at comparable stages, which changes how clips interact with the plant.
  </p>

  <p>
    A slightly larger clip allows the stem to expand during healing without becoming constricted. This is important because tomatoes continue growing actively through the grafting process.
  </p>

  <p>
    Using clips that are too small often leads to subtle damage—reduced flow through the graft or delayed healing that lowers success rates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Silicone Clips Are the Best Default</h2>

  <p>
    Silicone clips provide consistent pressure while allowing for slight movement as the plant grows.
  </p>

  <p>
    This flexibility reduces the risk of crushing the stem while still holding the graft firmly in place. It also makes them easier to apply without disturbing alignment.
  </p>

  <p>
    In contrast, rigid clips can shift during placement or apply uneven pressure, especially on slightly irregular stems.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in Tomato Grafting Clips</h2>

  <p>
    A few practical features determine whether clips are easy to use and reliable during healing.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Correct diameter range.</strong> The clip should match the stem size at grafting time.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Flexible material.</strong> Allows for growth without restricting the stem.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Secure but gentle pressure.</strong> Enough to hold alignment without crushing tissue.</p>

  <p>
    <strong>Easy removal or drop-off.</strong> Clips should fall away naturally as the plant thickens.</p>

  <p>
    These details affect both ease of use and success rates.
  </p>
</section>

