<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When These Clips Work Best</h2>

  <p>
    Grafting clips are most effective when timing and plant conditions are aligned.
  </p>

  <p>
    They work best when:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>scion and rootstock stems are similar in size</strong></p>

  <p>
    <strong>plants are actively growing</strong>, supporting faster healing</p>

  <p>
    <strong>recovery conditions are controlled</strong>, especially humidity and light</p>

  <p>
    In these conditions, clips provide stable support rather than compensating for mismatches.
  </p>

  <p>
    This timing often depends on coordinated seed starting, since knowing <a href="/guides/when-to-start-seeds-indoors/">when to start seeds indoors</a> helps ensure both plants reach the right stage together.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Clip Choice Won’t Fix the Problem</h2>

  <p>
    Clips can’t compensate for poor grafting conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    They are less effective when:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>stems are mismatched in size</strong></p>

  <p>
    <strong>plants are stressed or not growing actively</strong></p>

  <p>
    <strong>humidity and healing conditions are inconsistent</strong></p>

  <p>
    In these cases, improving technique and environment matters more than changing clip types.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Grafting Clips Actually Fail</h2>

  <p>
    Most failures come from subtle issues rather than obvious mistakes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Clips that are too tight can restrict flow through the graft, while loose clips allow movement that breaks alignment. Both reduce the chance of a successful union.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another common issue is shifting during placement. Even slight misalignment at the start can prevent proper healing.
  </p>

  <p>
    These problems are often mistaken for plant issues, but they usually trace back to clip sizing and handling.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Clip Choice vs Technique</h2>

  <p>
    Clip selection matters, but technique matters more.
  </p>

  <p>
    Clean cuts, precise alignment, and stable recovery conditions have a larger impact on success than small differences between clip types.
  </p>

  <p>
    The clip supports the graft—it doesn’t determine the outcome on its own.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    Start with 2.5–3.0 mm silicone grafting clips and keep a smaller size available for thinner seedlings. This covers most tomato grafting scenarios without adding unnecessary complexity.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Proper sizing and timing matter most.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best grafting clips for tomato seedlings are the ones that match stem size, apply gentle pressure, and maintain alignment throughout the healing process.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Consistent support leads to stronger grafts.
  </p>
</section>